    <div class="header">
        <h1>The Evolution of Games: From Sacred Rituals to Playing Cards</h1>
        <p>A journey through humanity's relationship with play, strategy, and chance</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="curator-statement">
        <h2>Curator's Statement</h2>
        <p>Games. Play. Ritual. Entertainment. Terms seemingly unrelated come together in humanity's evolution from divine omens to naturalized recreation. My curatorial practice eschews chronology in favor of a polyphonic debate of questioning liminalities in which divine transcendence intersects with ludic representation. Why is Senet's path to the underworld compelling for millennia on end? Why do ivory dice turn to cardboard democracy? Play's epistemological foundations are deconstructed by the chronology.</p>
        
        <p>Resisting linear temporality, I've taken on a tripartite form: numinous origins (games as theurgical technology), classical deification (epistemology of war in strategic thought), revolution of democratization (paper's material dialectic). Games cross boundaries with mercantile relentlessness but transform with chameleonic malleability. Such is the paradox represented by the Indo-Persian-European meandering of Chaturanga: same strategic DNA but radically different cultural phenotypes.</p>
        
        <p>Three technological convergences characterize gaming's past: paper's democratization, Gutenberg's standardization, commodification by mass production. Not teleological fulfillment but generative nexus is the American deck: ancient Egyptian afterlife journeys condensed to fifty-two cards, limitless possibility condensed to determinate shape.</p>
    </div>    </div>
    
    <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 3100 BCE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Egypt</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Senet - The Game of Passing</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The earliest known board game, Senet represented the journey of the soul through the afterlife. Found in Egyptian tombs, it reveals humanity's first fusion of play with spiritual beliefs, establishing games as more than mere entertainment.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 2600 BCE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Mesopotamia</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Royal Game of Ur</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">This racing game combined strategy with chance using tetrahedral dice. Its popularity across social classes demonstrates games' role in bridging societal divides and establishing common cultural experiences.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 2000 BCE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">China</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Liubo - The Six Sticks Game</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">An ancient Chinese divination game that combined cosmic symbolism with gameplay. Players used six sticks as dice, connecting earthly entertainment with celestial order, showing games' role in understanding the universe.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="era-marker">~ The Classical Age of Strategy ~</div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1500 BCE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">India</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Dice Games in the Rigveda</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The oldest literary reference to dice games appears in Hindu scripture, warning of gambling's dangers while acknowledging its irresistible appeal. This marks the beginning of games as subjects of moral and philosophical discourse.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 800 BCE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Greece</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Petteia - The Ancient Strategy Game</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">A predecessor to chess, Petteia involved moving pieces on a board to capture opponents. It represented the Greek ideal of strategic thinking and military planning, influencing later European game development.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 600 BCE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">India</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Chaturanga - The Birth of Chess</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The ancestor of chess, representing a four-division army (infantry, cavalry, elephants, chariots). This game revolutionized strategic thinking and would spread across the world, becoming the foundation for modern chess.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 500 BCE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">China</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Go (Weiqi) - The Game of Stones</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">Perhaps the most complex board game ever created, Go represents the balance of power and territory. Its simple rules but infinite complexity mirror Chinese philosophical concepts of yin and yang, demonstrating games as vehicles for deep thought.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 400 BCE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Rome</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Tabula - Roman Backgammon</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">Romans refined this race game, making it a favorite across the empire. Tabula's popularity among all social classes helped establish gaming as a universal human activity, transcending cultural and economic boundaries.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 200 BCE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">China</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Xiangqi - Chinese Chess</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">Evolved from Chaturanga but adapted to Chinese military concepts, featuring a river between armies and different piece movements. This adaptation showed how games evolve to reflect local cultures and values.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="era-marker">~ The Medieval Gaming Renaissance ~</div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 600 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Persia</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Shatranj - Persian Chess</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The Persian adaptation of Chaturanga that would eventually reach Europe through Islamic conquest. Shatranj preserved strategic gaming during the Dark Ages and served as the bridge between ancient and modern chess.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 700 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">China</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Domino Cards - Paper Gaming Begins</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The earliest paper-based games emerged in China, combining domino patterns with card format. This innovation marked the beginning of portable gaming and the democratization of games through cheaper materials.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1000 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">China</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Playing Cards Invented</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The first true playing cards appeared during the Tang Dynasty, featuring suits and court cards. This revolutionary gaming format would eventually spread worldwide, fundamentally changing how games were designed and played.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1070 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Europe</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Modern Chess Rules Established</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">Chess evolved from Shatranj in medieval Europe, with the queen and bishop gaining their modern powers. This transformation reflected changing European society and created the strategic masterpiece we know today.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1200 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Europe</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Backgammon Codified</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">Medieval Europeans standardized backgammon rules, creating the modern game. This codification process became a model for how games could be preserved and transmitted across cultures and generations.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1360 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Europe</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Playing Cards Arrive in Europe</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">Islamic traders brought playing cards to Europe through Spain and Italy. European adoption and adaptation of card games marked the beginning of the modern card gaming tradition that would dominate Western entertainment.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1377 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Europe</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">First European Card Game Records</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The first documented European card games appear in records from Switzerland and Germany. These early references show how quickly card games spread and became integral to European social life.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1400 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Europe</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Tarot Cards Developed</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">Originally created for the game of tarocchi, not divination, tarot cards introduced the concept of trump cards. This innovation would influence card game design for centuries and create one of gaming's most enduring mechanics.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1440 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">Germany</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Gutenberg and Mass-Produced Cards</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The printing press revolutionized card production, making decks affordable and standardized. This technological breakthrough democratized gaming and enabled the spread of uniform rules across vast distances.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1480 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">France</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">French Suit System Established</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The French created the four-suit system (hearts, diamonds, clubs, spades) that would become the global standard. This elegant design balanced simplicity with versatility, creating the foundation for modern card games.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1500 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">France</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Piquet - The Game of Kings</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">This sophisticated two-player card game became the favorite of French nobility and refined card play to an art form. Piquet demonstrated how card games could embody social sophistication and intellectual challenge.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1600 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">England</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Cribbage Invented</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">Sir John Suckling created cribbage, combining card play with mathematical scoring. This game showed how innovation could create new gaming experiences from familiar elements, influencing game design philosophy.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1700 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">England</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Whist Emerges</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">Whist evolved from earlier trick-taking games to become the premier partnership card game. Its emphasis on skill and partnership play influenced social gaming culture and established patterns still used in modern card games.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1750 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">America</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Colonial Card Games</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">European card games crossed the Atlantic with colonists, adapting to frontier life. These games provided entertainment and social connection in isolated communities, demonstrating gaming's role in cultural preservation and adaptation.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1800 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">America</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">American Card Manufacturing</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">American companies began producing playing cards domestically, establishing the design standards that would become the modern American deck. This marked America's emergence as a gaming culture in its own right.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry left">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1850 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">America</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Poker Develops</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">American poker emerged from various European games, adding the uniquely American elements of bluffing and betting. This innovation would become America's greatest contribution to world gaming culture.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="timeline-entry right">
            <div class="timeline-marker"></div>
            <div class="timeline-content">
                <div class="timeline-date"><span class="icon"></span>c. 1860 CE</div>
                <div class="timeline-location">America</div>
                <div class="timeline-title">Standardized American Deck</div>
                <div class="timeline-description">The modern 52-card deck with jokers and standardized court card designs was established. This format became the global standard, representing the culmination of centuries of evolution in card design and gaming culture.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <script>
        // Add smooth scrolling and enhanced interactions
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
            const entries = document.querySelectorAll('.timeline-entry');
            
            // Alternating layout
            entries.forEach((entry, index) => {
                if (index % 2 === 0) {
                    entry.classList.add('left');
                } else {
                    entry.classList.add('right');
                }
            });
            
            // Stagger animation delays
            entries.forEach((entry, index) => {
                entry.style.animationDelay = (index * 0.1) + 's';
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
